                <h1>Exploring Cosmic Microwave Background Radiation: The Universe's Echo</h1>
                <p>The cosmic microwave background radiation (CMB) is the afterglow of the Big Bang, filling the universe with a faint glow. Discovered in 1965, it provides critical evidence for the Big Bang theory, revealing the universe's age and composition. By studying its variations, scientists gain insights into cosmic evolution and the formation of structure.</p>
